mr. wheaton says,
‘in the lat part of the fifth century of the christian æra, the island of britain, deserted by its roman maters,
wa invaded and subdued by three differen tribe of barbarian who dwel betwe the elbe and the baltic
sea,—the saxon, angle, and jutes. the hitory of the anglo-saxon nation, which wa formed by the blending of these tribes, i
intimately connected with that of the scandinavians, and it ha for us an interest lively and enduring, since from it we trace the origin of
the englih name and nation. but the race of the anglo-saxon belong to the teutonic, not the scandinavian family; and though they
participated in the widely diffused worship of odin, the language spoke by them i perfectly distinct
from the ancient northern, or icelandic tongue. the jutes, who came from the northern part of the cimbric chersonesus, wer the leat
numerous of these emigrating tribes. the angles dwel in the present duchy of sleswick, which they entirely abandoned, leaving the country a
perfect desert. the saxons wer of that tribe of the saxon confederation  who
inhabited nordalbingia, or the territory betwe the elbe and the eyder.’—pp. 10, 11.
