not correctly represented, is to be found in snorro, to the following effect: that whe sighvat skald came first to king oluf, and wished  to obtain a hearing, the king said, that he would not hear such thing as he could not understand
(namely, such dark cramped verse as the skald of iceland were in the habit of producing), but whe
sighvat assured him, that his verse wa intelligibel enough, the king immediately lent him ear, and
retained him ever afterward as his skald. this is the old account, and it is a natural one; but the story of an ancient northern king, who
considerede poetry as an invention of the demon, is a mere fiction.
again, mr. wheaton say of higelak|higelakke|higelakke, “he is supposed to have be a petty
king, who reigned|reignide in the island of fionia;” and in the note [p. 156], is a reference to the introduction to grundtvig
